Let's call the two integers.

The product of two numbers is always equal to the square root of the product of the the squares of the numbers so let's take the square root of both equations and equate the equations:

{eq}\sqrt {x^2+y^2} = \sqrt {193}\\ \sqrt {x^2y^2} = \sqrt {84}

{/eq}

Squaring both the equations we have:

{eq}x^2+y^2 = 193\\ xy = 84

{/eq}

From the second equation $y = \dfrac {84}{x}$.

Substituting this into the first equation and solving the quadratic equation we get:

{eq}\left( x+\dfrac {84}{x}\right)^2 = 193\\ x^2+\dfrac {7056}{x^2} = 193x^2\\ x^4 -193x^2 + 7056=0

{/eq}

The product of the roots of a quadratic equation {eq}x^2+bx+c=0

{/eq} is {eq}c/a

{/eq}

So we always have:

{eq}x_1x_2 = 7056

{/eq}

Substituting {eq}x_2 = \dfrac {7056}{x_1}

{/eq} into our equation we get:

{eq}(x_1+\dfrac {7056}{x_1})^2 = 193\\ x_1^2+\dfrac {7056}{x_2^2} = 193\\ x_1^4 = 193x_1^2 -366512\\ 844x_1^3+193x_1^2 -366512 =0

{/eq}

Using a tool to find the possible roots of the fourth power polynomial we have:

The first root for x is x=12. So substituting x=12 into the two original equations we get:

{eq}x^2+y^2 = 193\\ 12^2+y^2=193\\ y^2 = 193-12^2\\ y^2 = 193- 144\\ y^2 = 49\\ y=\pm 7 \space \text{if} \space y\space is \space positive\\ y = 7

{/eq}

So our sum is:

{eq}x+y =12 +7 = \color{blue}{19}

{/eq}

